raw_data.title: Lead Penetration Tester
raw_data.description: A Lead Penetration Tester is responsible for leading and conducting comprehensive security assessments to identify vulnerabilities within an organization's systems, applications, and networks. This role involves planning and executing penetration tests, coordinating Red Team engagements, and delivering detailed reports with actionable remediation recommendations. The Lead Penetration Tester also mentors junior team members, stays updated on emerging threats and attack techniques, and collaborates with stakeholders to enhance the organization's security posture. Proficiency in tools such as Burp Suite, Metasploit, and Kali Linux, along with certifications like OSCP or GPEN, is typically required.

raw_data.title: Penetration Tester
raw_data.description: A Penetration Tester, also known as an ethical hacker, is responsible for evaluating the security of computer systems, networks, and applications by simulating cyberattacks. Their primary goal is to identify vulnerabilities that malicious actors could exploit. This involves conducting thorough assessments using both automated tools and manual techniques, including network scanning, vulnerability assessments, and social engineering tactics. After identifying potential weaknesses, penetration testers document their findings in detailed reports, providing actionable recommendations to enhance security measures. They must stay current with the latest cybersecurity threats and trends to effectively protect organizational assets.

raw_data.title: Secure Code Analysis
raw_data.description: A Secure Code Analyst specializes in identifying and mitigating security vulnerabilities within software applications by reviewing source code for potential risks. They utilize both manual and automated techniques, including static and dynamic analysis tools, to detect issues such as improper input validation, authentication flaws, and insecure cryptographic practices. Collaborating closely with development teams, they provide actionable recommendations to remediate identified vulnerabilities and ensure adherence to secure coding standards. Additionally, Secure Code Analysts contribute to the development of secure coding guidelines and conduct training sessions to promote security awareness among developers.

raw_data.title: SAST O&M & Integration Specialist
raw_data.description: A Static Application Security Testing (SAST) Operations & Maintenance (O&M) & Integration Specialist is responsible for overseeing the deployment, maintenance, and integration of SAST tools within an organization's software development lifecycle. This role involves configuring and optimizing SAST solutions, ensuring seamless integration with existing development environments, and providing ongoing support to address performance issues and updates. The specialist collaborates with development and security teams to establish best practices for secure coding and continuous security testing. Additionally, they monitor tool effectiveness, troubleshoot integration challenges, and contribute to the evolution of the organization's security posture by recommending enhancements and ensuring compliance with industry standards.

raw_data.title: DAST Lead
raw_data.description: A DAST Lead (Dynamic Application Security Testing Lead) is responsible for overseeing and executing dynamic security assessments to identify vulnerabilities in web applications and APIs. This role involves leading a team of security professionals, managing the integration of DAST tools into the software development lifecycle, and ensuring comprehensive coverage of potential security threats. The DAST Lead collaborates closely with development and operations teams to prioritize and remediate identified vulnerabilities, enhancing the organization's overall security posture. Additionally, they stay informed about emerging threats and best practices to continuously improve the effectiveness of security testing efforts.

raw_data.title: Threat Simulation Environment Admin
raw_data.description: A Threat Simulation Environment Administrator is responsible for managing and optimizing environments that emulate cyber threats to assess and enhance an organization's security posture. This role involves configuring and maintaining simulation platforms, integrating threat intelligence data, and conducting realistic attack scenarios to evaluate system vulnerabilities. The administrator collaborates with security teams to ensure that simulations accurately reflect potential adversary tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs). Additionally, they analyze simulation results to provide actionable insights for strengthening defenses and improving incident response strategies. Proficiency in simulation tools, threat modeling, and a strong understanding of cybersecurity principles are essential for success in this position.

raw_data.title: HVA Pentration Tester
raw_data.description: A High-Value Asset (HVA) Penetration Tester specializes in assessing the security of critical systems and infrastructures, such as financial networks, energy grids, and government operations. This role involves simulating advanced persistent threats (APTs) to identify vulnerabilities that could be exploited by adversaries. The tester employs a combination of manual and automated techniques, including exploiting zero-day vulnerabilities, bypassing security controls, and conducting social engineering attacks. Collaboration with senior security teams is essential to develop tailored attack scenarios and to provide actionable recommendations for enhancing system defenses. Given the sensitivity of the assets involved, this role often requires a high level of security clearance and adherence to strict ethical standards.

(Ensure that images comply with prevailing Federal and customer policies and requirements).
